}} also referred to by its acronym 'UEFA' ( )) is the
administrative body for association football in Europe and, partially, Asia. It
is one of six continental confederations of world football's governing body
FIFA. UEFA consists of fifty-four national associations members.

UEFA represents the national football associations of Europe, runs nation and
club competitions including the UEFA European Championship, UEFA Champions
League, UEFA Europa League, and UEFA Super Cup, and controls the prize money,
regulations and media rights to those competitions.

UEFA was founded on 15 June 1954 in Basel after consultation between the
Italian, French, and Belgian associations. Initially, the European football
union consisted of 25 members which number doubled by the early 1990s. Not all
sovereign countries of Europe are members of UEFA, yet all non-members are micro
states. Several Asian countries were also admitted to the European football
association, particularly Israel and Kazakhstan, which had been members of the
Asian football association.

Until 1959 the main headquarters were located in Paris, and later in Bern. Since
1995, UEFA headquarters transferred to Nyon, Switzerland. Henri Delaunay was the
first General Secretary and Ebbe Schwartz the first president. The current
president is Michel Platini.
